\par }\pard\plain \s16\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\nooverflow\faroman\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f1\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {This review list is provided to in
form you about the document in question and assist you in its preparation.  Terminating your guarantee only limits your liabilities from the date received by the party who has your guarantee.  Therefore, you must send it by registered mail, by courier wit
h signature required, or by a recognized overnight delivery service by a firm such as FedEx.
\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\nooverflow\faroman\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f1\fs22 
\par You 
should only take this action if you believe the party whose debt you are guaranteeing will continue to make payments against the guarantee outstanding and the party holding the guarantee will not just use this to call the debt and therefore put you back i
n the same place you were before, except matters may be even worse now if you have triggered a default on the matter.
\par 
\par These terminations are usually used by principals in businesses who no longer have those roles and whose guarantees were secondary, or good faith, guarantees of the debts in question.   In these instances, the Termination 
can be very helpful over the long term to extricate you from these contingent liabilities.  I have made use of this approach effectively in the past when selling a business or transferring management roles to another party.
\par 
\par The key cautionary note is to avoid taking this action if you believe it will trigger a default which, in turn, will weaken the original party and put your guarantee front and center for collection by the holder of your guarantee.  Watch out for this boom
erang problem. 
\par }}